# JFTL reference test corpus, v3 — corrects the expression-engine prefixes
# and adds an explicit LEVEL= field to every test. Supersedes
# jftl_reference_tests_v2.txt (same 121 cases, source lines ~1-1105 of 2635).
#
# ID naming: NNN-tag, tag is one of: nav, logic, py, eval, run, skip.
# LEVEL=<tag> is also included as its own field on every non-skip test
# (redundant with the ID suffix, per request).
#
# Corrected expression-engine syntax:
#   $py=<expr>     - simpleeval (EvalWithCompoundTypes), restricted to your
#                    whitelist: arithmetic/comparison/boolean/ternary,
#                    subscript/slice, "in"/"not in", list/tuple/dict/set
#                    literals AND comprehensions, functions {len, min, max,
#                    sum, round, range, sorted}, string methods {join,
#                    lower, upper, strip, rstrip, replace, split} (see bug
#                    note below on startswith/endswith).
#   $pyeval=<expr> - unrestricted eval() of a single Python expression: any
#                    builtin, any method, module access via __import__(...).
#   $pyrun=<code>  - exec-style, real statements (loops, assignments,
#                    multiple lines), final result given via an explicit
#                    "return" — used only when genuine imperative/recursive
#                    logic is unavoidable.
#   $.path         - navigation, unchanged.
#
# Tier definitions (unchanged from v2, just the prefixes were wrong there):
#   nav   - whole template is a literal/object/array skeleton whose leaves
#           are JSON literals or a bare "$.path" string. No {"$":true}
#           anywhere.
#   logic - uses {"$":true} (set/if/foreach/case/data/transform/default) but
#           never reads a named variable's value through an expression
#           engine. Main trick: foreach with no "var" sets frame.current to
#           the item each iteration, so body "$." re-emits it for free.
#   py    - needs $py= and stays inside the whitelist above.
#   eval  - needs $pyeval= (something outside the whitelist, still one
#           expression).
#   run   - needs $pyrun= (real statements/loops; forcing it into a single
#           expression would be a hack, not idiomatic).
#   skip  - no JFTL section; SKIP=<short reason> instead, no LEVEL field.
#
# Found while deriving the "py" whitelist: STRING_ATTRS is missing a comma
# between "startswith" and "endswith", so they silently concatenate into one
# unusable entry. Classified below as if both work (matching evident
# intent) — worth fixing on your end.
#
# STATUS: still chunk 1 only (source lines ~1-1105 of 2635). None of this is
# engine-verified (no sandbox this session).

